summary: The Tooth and Claw Josh-the-Werewolf story, as told by David Tennant at the Dallas Fan Expo, 2017.    Source con video: [ x ]...
caption:
The Tooth and Claw Josh-the-Werewolf story, as told by David Tennant at the Dallas Fan Expo, 2017.   
Source con video: [ x ]

Full text of David’s story:

When we did the werewolf episode - it was called Tooth & Claw - the werewolf was created in a computer by the geniuses at the Mill who were were our cgi experts, but it’s represented on set somehow or another usually, for an eye-line or for a reference for the people who then replace the image.  So we had a guy who had a bicycle helmet with a thing on the end to show where the head of the creature would be.  He was in a lycra bodysuit, and he would sort of… go around… [mimes werewolf movements] …which was fine and great and he did it extremely well, but it was very tight, this thing he was in.  

I hope he won’t mind me mentioning it, but a couple of days in, maybe not even a couple of days, somebody noticed that this left very little to the imagination, and this boy, was a boy!   I mean, it would have taken your eye out. Terribly impressive.  Awe inspiring.  It inspired awe! 

…and the trouble is, once you’ve noticed that, it’s quite hard to keep your eyeline on the tennis ball that’s coming out of the stick on top of his head, because the eye is being drawn for whatever your reasoning might be, whether its awe or envy or just the sheer record-breaking dimensions

I don’t know if it crept up on a Doctor Who Confidential or anything but it’s worth checking out 

Bonus:

summary:
According to Neil Gaiman, David Tennant and Michael Sheen are positively divine.

 The pair star in the upcoming Amazon TV...
text:
According to Neil Gaiman, David Tennant and Michael Sheen are positively divine.

The pair star in the upcoming Amazon TV series Good Omens, based on the beloved 1990 satire novel by Gaiman and Terry Pratchett. The story follows a whole host of quirky characters trying to navigate the end of the world — including a young Antichrist, a prescient witch, and the Four Bikers of the Apocalypse. But the real heart of Good Omens is Sheen and Tennant’s characters: a bookkeeper angel named Aziraphale and a sunglasses-sporting demon named Crowley. Together, they try to defy their demonic and angelic overlords and prevent the apocalypse.

Gaiman and director Douglas Mackinnon stopped by the EW studio at Comic-Con to tease a little bit about Tennant and Sheen’s chemistry and what to expect from the unlikely pair.

“I gave them good lines and Terry gave them good lines, but they brought the magic,” Gaiman said. “And it is that chocolate and peanut butter thing, where they taste good individually, but you put them together, and now you’ve got something special.”

“Putting them together is like Scotland’s favorite actor and Wales’ favorite actor together on screen for the first time,” Mackinnon added. “And they were magical from the read through forward. At the read-through, you could actually see them becoming a team. It’s just there on the screen. It’s a thing that you can’t really specify why it works, but it just works.
